Riverbed
The river here is broad, shallow, and  slow-moving.    Sunlight filters down on you as you slip easily through the refreshingly cool water.    You see a few piranha, distant relatives of your friend in the tank, but they're smaller and less fond of fingers, and don't give you any trouble.   You can climb a wooden ramp to the north and board the Murdered Mermaid or swim east, into the deep basin of churning water under the waterfall.   To the west, the river narrows and rushes quickly over jagged rocks, making it impossible to safely swim in that direction.

> e

> e

Waterfall Lake
You're in a basin full of churning water.  It's difficult to swim steadily, and yet seeing the bottom of a waterfall from such an unfamiliar vantage point is somehow soothing and exciting at the same time.    The river flows west, and there's a narrow strip of grassy bank to the north, running along the bottom of the cliff.  You can also see a glow coming from an underwater cave entrance  just to the northeast.

> ne

> ne
You swim into the underwater passage, following streaks of glowing moss along the walls.   Soon you breach the surface and continue crawling along the upward slope of the tunnel, your hands and knees complaining as you penetrate deep, deep into the rock of the cliff.     You turn a corner and the glow brightens, dazzling you.  At the same time, your questing hand meets only air, and you topple forward with a cry, landing on your back on what feets like a gym mat.   It takes you a moment to get your breath back and look around.

The Blue Shrine
You are standing in a circular stone room which stretches up farther than you can see.   The first thirty feet or so are visible in the eerie blue light of the phosphorescent moss covering the walls, but beyond that is darkness.   The blue bands twist around the walls, leading the eye towards an enormous clam resting in a pool of water. The only visible exit is to the southwest, where a block of stone is missing about ten feet up, directly above a shriveled-up mushroom.
