> n
You carefully descend into the dark and forbidding jungle.

Primeval Trail
You're standing in thick, greenish purple shrubbery, with dark, twisted palms rising around you on all sides.  A path winds its way through the trees to the northeast, and the Great Gate to the south looks scalable.
You can hear murmuring, chittering, and the occasional shriek coming from the northeast trail, and behind it all, a group of high-pitched voices raised in a screechy, off-key song.

> ne

> ne
As you step into the clearing, the song falls silent, and you gasp.  You've stepped from the jungle into a lovely Parisian cityscape.  It's built at a one-tenth scale and constructed of grass and bamboo, but you know Paris when you see it.  You've got postcards.

There's not a soul around.   Obviously, you're about as popular here as Elliot Ness at a New Year's Eve party.

A Quaint Upper-Middle-Class Parisian Neighborhood
This is a small Paris cityscape made of grass and bamboo.  It's eerily empty, as far as you can see, and yet you feel like you're being watched from every window.    The road leads away to the southwest and to the north.   There's no Eiffel tower, but you can see a recreation of the Fontaine des Innocents, which burbles water from some underground spring, and  a scale model of the Cathedral of Notre-Dame sits in the middle of the city.

You can see the Notre Dame Cathedral and the Fontaine des Innocents.
> x fontaine

> x fontaine
This beautiful fontaine was painstakingly constructed out of carved coconuts and banana paste as a perfect scale replication of the original.  It's surrounded by bas reliefs of monkey nymphs dressed in diaphanous robes.   Cold, refreshing water bubbles up from the center.  It's a drinking fontaine.
> x cathedral

> x cathedral
A  scale model of the Cathedral of Notre-Dame, built out of grass and vines and buttressed by bamboo.   Beautiful stained-sap windows line the exterior. It's probably the only building here you might actually be able to fit inside.
> in

> in
You get down on all fours and wriggle through the cathedral doors.  It turns out you can only make it halfway in due to an inconveniently large buttress getting in your way, but that's far enough to take a look around.

Notre Dame Cathedral Nave
Your front half is lying uncomfortably in the nave of the Notre-Dame Cathedral.    It's like a dollhouse inside--cute little pews carved out of coconut, teensy little hymnals made of scraps of paper bound together, the whole shebang.  Beautiful stained-sap windows line the walls, and a strange collection of objects--maybe left by previous explorers--are piled up behind the altar.  You can't reach any of it, though.   There's a large trapdoor in the floor which might lead somewhere if you could get to it, only you can't, and frankly, sister, barring a sudden attack of the shrinks you'd have an easier time lifting the whole cathedral over your head than getting through this entryway.
You can see a wilderness survival kit, a map of Darkest Golanaland, a box of flares, a working radio, a Genevieve Yee designer thermos flask, an elephant gun, an useless doorknob and a trapdoor.
