As the frosty pureed banana slides down your throat, you feel you mind seeming to inflate like a balloon.   You're rising up and out of yourself, and at the same time, you're falling, falling into the cup, into a sea of fruity yellow.  In that sea floats the United States, with some wiggly knobs on either side that might be Canada and Mexico, because this is all in your head, and you don't remember what they're shaped like very well.

You fall through the clouds, through the smog, and through the tarpaper roof of a leaky old tenement, the kind a junior reporter who was the office ashtray dumper six months ago might be able to afford.  It's your apartment.  You're back in your own apartment.

