In a few easy hops, you descend back into the lush jungle.

The Great Stone Gate
A seventy-foot stone wall juts from the earth here, slicing through the jungle.  It was once elaborately carved, but is so old that much of the decoration has worn away, and the crumbling stonework is home to mosses, ferns, and even a few small trees that have managed to take root in the gaps between the blocks.   The  dirt path leads south into the trees and north up to a gate fit for a giant, made of enormous trees that have petrified over the aeons.  It's unlikely that you'll be able to get the gate open, but a good enough climber might be able to make it north over the wall.

> s

> s

A Tangle of Roots
You are in a gnarled tangle of enormous roots at the foot of the tree.    A broad, worn path travels past you in a north-south direction, and the heaps of crumbling stonework visible through the roots seems to indicate that there was once some sort of a building where the tree now grows.   High above you, you can just make out the plane tangled in the branches.

> warp to plane

> warp to plane
The sensation is like zooming up on elevator shoes.  There are three pops as you appear inside the plane--the usual one, and both your ears.

The Spirit of Fresno
You're in the cabin of The Spirit of Fresno, the plucky little plane that couldn't.    It's missing its roof, both wings, and the exit door, and leaves are drifting down from the damaged canopy above.   A thick branch has torn through the floor, revealing a dizzying drop to the underbrush far below.

Golden light filters through the metal frame, making a lattice of shadows on the floor.

You can see a Guidebook to Golanaland, a burst golanut, flying squirrels and a radio.
> use component on radio

> use component on radio
The vital component snaps easily back into place within the radio.  That certainly was convenient, and not at all a roundabout pain in the hindquarters.  Now you can USE the radio to call for help!
> turn on radio

> turn on radio
The cabin is filled with the jaunty sounds of Bix Bigby and his Big Boy Band.
> use radio

> use radio
"Mayday, mayday, this is Jacqueline McBean.  I'm stranded in the jungle, please respond..."

It takes few minutes of frantic calling, but you finally manage to get in touch with a ham radio operator in the city who relays your plight to the proper authorities, and not long after that, you're being escorted out of the jungle by a rescue party.   You arrive in the Big Golanut only slightly delayed, ready to take on your dream job.  Nobody knows what really happened to you; nobody knows about the idols and the shrines and everything else, and would they even believe you?   As time passes, even this exciting new life settles into a sort of routine, and your experiences in the jungle are the ones that feel like a dream...
...except once a Jungle Queen, always a Jungle Queen, apparently, because you've still got all those crackerjack special abilities.   What's more, they're proving very useful to aspiring raker of muck such as yourself.  Whether it's scaling a building through the way of the gecko, using rain and heat to flush a recalcitrant interviewee out of hiding, or simply warping to the scene faster than anyone else, you're the girl with an arsenal of secret weapons and the will to use 'em.
Pulitzer, here you come!
